  'You are performing a specialty locational analysis at 412 Traction Street, Greenville, SC 29601. The subject is 3BR/2BA · 1,440 SF · 1940-built SFR (renovated 2022) · West End / Railroad District. Specialty appraisal — West End Greenville property with three interacting specialty characteristics: (1) active STR license in the City of Greenville overlay zone; (2) location within a City-designated historic overlay district; and (3) adjacency to the Railroad District mixed-use entertainment corridor. The appraiser must identify and classify all locational factors and address how each interacts with all three specialty characteristics simultaneously. Section 5 — Locational Influence — requires you to identify which locational factors are present at the subject, classify each as Positive, Negative, Neutral, or Market-Dependent based on the location profile evidence and the specialty framework, and write a brief market-supported rationale for each classification. Specialty assignments require the appraiser to identify the relevant specialty characteristics first (waterfront tier, ADU, STR, mountain market, etc.) and then analyze every locational factor through the lens of those characteristics simultaneously. Distractor factors that are not present must be left unchecked, and each rationale must cite specific evidence and connect the factor to the relevant specialty framework.'
FROM scenario_categories WHERE code = 'M2-S5-C6';

INSERT INTO model_answers
  (scenario_id, field_id, answer_text, field_options_override, model_data)
SELECT
  s.id,
  f.id,
  '',
  '{"subject": {"address_summary": "412 Traction Street, Greenville, SC 29601", "subject_summary": "3BR/2BA · 1,440 SF · 1940-built SFR (renovated 2022) · West End / Railroad District", "context_label": "Specialty Context", "context_text": "Specialty appraisal — West End Greenville property with three interacting specialty characteristics: (1) active STR license in the City of Greenville overlay zone; (2) location within a City-designated historic overlay district; and (3) adjacency to the Railroad District mixed-use entertainment corridor. The appraiser must identify and classify all locational factors and address how each interacts with all three specialty characteristics simultaneously."}, "location_profile": ["The subject is a renovated bungalow in the West End / Railroad District, approximately 0.5 miles from Main Street and 0.3 miles from the Swamp Rabbit Trail northern terminus. The Railroad District is an active mixed-use corridor with adaptive reuse projects, breweries, restaurants, and event venues that have opened since 2016. The City of Greenville historic overlay district governs exterior modifications to the subject; the STR overlay zone covers this address with current licensing available.", "412 Traction Street is a through-street lot of 0.12 acres with a 20-foot setback. A brewery and event venue operates approximately 150 feet from the subject — evening and weekend operations with amplified music and parking activity documented by listing agent notes. The City''s STR ordinance is under active review with proposed amendments that may cap new STR licenses in the Railroad District overlay. The school zone is below-average for Greenville County. FEMA Zone X is confirmed. Prisma Health downtown campus is approximately 0.9 miles east."], "factors": [{"id": "A", "label": "Downtown Greenville proximity (0.5 miles, walkable)"}, {"id": "B", "label": "Swamp Rabbit Trail terminus proximity (0.3 miles)"}, {"id": "C", "label": "Railroad District mixed-use energy (breweries, restaurants, event venues)"}, {"id": "D", "label": "Brewery / event venue (~150 ft, evening noise and parking activity)"}, {"id": "E", "label": "Active STR license (currently licensed under City overlay)"}, {"id": "F", "label": "STR ordinance under active review (proposed caps in Railroad District)"}, {"id": "G", "label": "Historic overlay district (design review requirements)"}, {"id": "H", "label": "Below-average school district"}, {"id": "I", "label": "FEMA Zone X"}, {"id": "J", "label": "Prisma Health employment proximity (~0.9 miles)"}, {"id": "K", "label": "Industrial adjacency or manufacturing nuisance"}, {"id": "L", "label": "FEMA Zone AE"}], "classification_options": ["Positive", "Negative", "Neutral", "Market-Dependent"], "min_rationale_chars": 20, "teaching_points": ["Teaching Point 1 — Three specialty characteristics require three simultaneous analytical lenses. Each factor must be evaluated through the STR lens, the historic overlay lens, and the Railroad District mixed-use lens simultaneously. Factor D (brewery noise) is a straightforward Negative for primary residential use but is a more complex factor for STR — some guests seek the entertainment district energy; others are deterred by noise. Specialty analysis requires the appraiser to hold multiple client-use dimensions in parallel throughout the classification process.", "Teaching Point 2 — STR license and STR regulatory risk are both present and analytically distinct. Factor E (active license) is Positive — a current use right with income value. Factor F (proposed ordinance caps) is Negative — potential loss of that right. Students who identify only one of these two factors are missing a material dimension of the STR specialty analysis. The gap between a current Positive use right and a threatened Negative regulatory change is precisely the analytical issue that a sophisticated specialty client needs quantified.", "Teaching Point 3 — Railroad District character is Market-Dependent, not Positive. Factor C is analytically distinct from Factor D (the specific brewery) and from Factor A (downtown proximity). Factor C addresses the broad district energy as a locational attribute — and buyer response to that energy is genuinely split. Students who default Positive for any vibrant neighborhood are substituting personal preference for market evidence. The analytical obligation is to identify the classification the market supports, not the one that most favorably represents the location."]}'::jsonb,
  '{"factors": {"A": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "Walkable downtown access at 0.5 miles is a primary demand driver for both STR guests and long-term professional renters — a Positive supporting all three specialty characteristics simultaneously."}, "B": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "Trail access within 0.3 miles is a documented Positive for STR guests seeking Greenville''s outdoor amenity and for professional renters prioritizing active lifestyle access."}, "C": {"present": true, "classification": "Market-Dependent", "rationale": "District energy is a lifestyle Positive for some STR guests and urban buyers; it is a deterrent for others who prefer quieter residential settings. Market-Dependent is analytically precise — buyer and guest response to mixed-use district character is genuinely split."}, "D": {"present": true, "classification": "Negative", "rationale": "A brewery and event venue 150 feet away with amplified music and parking activity is a documented Negative — an immediate proximity externality that constrains both the residential tenant pool and STR guest satisfaction."}, "E": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "A current STR license under the City overlay zone is a Positive — a documented use right with income value in the Greenville STR market."}, "F": {"present": true, "classification": "Negative", "rationale": "Active regulatory review trending toward STR caps is a Negative — potential loss of the current use right is a determinable adverse outcome regardless of individual buyer preference."}, "G": {"present": true, "classification": "Market-Dependent", "rationale": "Overlay restrictions on exterior modifications produce split buyer response — some value character preservation; others find the approval process burdensome. Market-Dependent requires paired sales from comparable historic overlay properties in this submarket."}, "H": {"present": true, "classification": "Negative", "rationale": "Below-average school zone constrains the owner-occupant resale pool — a Negative for long-term exit strategy."}, "I": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "Zone X confirmed."}, "J": {"present": true, "classification": "Positive", "rationale": "Medical employment proximity at 0.9 miles supports the long-term professional rental market — a Positive that supplements STR demand with a stable long-term tenant alternative."}, "K": {"present": false}, "L": {"present": false}}}'::jsonb
FROM scenarios s
JOIN scenario_categories sc ON sc.id = s.category_id
JOIN module_sections ms ON ms.id = sc.section_id
JOIN section_fields f ON f.section_id = ms.id AND f.field_key = 'factor_analysis'
WHERE sc.code = 'M2-S5-C6'
